# removing the outliers using Z
from scipy.stats import zscore

# Function to remove outliers using Z-score
def remove_outliers_using_zscore(df, column, threshold=3):
    z_scores = zscore(df[column])
    df_filtered = df[(abs(z_scores) < threshold)]
    return df_filtered

# Remove outliers using Z-score for numerical columns
threshold = 3  # Adjust this threshold as needed
for column in numerical_columns:
    df = remove_outliers_using_zscore(df, column, threshold)

# Separate the target column (HeartDisease) from the feature columns
target_column = 'HeartDisease'
features_columns = df.drop(columns=[target_column])

# Apply Min-Max scaling to all numerical columns (excluding the target column)
min_max_scaler = MinMaxScaler()
features_columns = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(features_columns)

# Apply Standardization (Z-score scaling) to all numerical columns (excluding the target column)
standard_scaler = StandardScaler()
features_columns = standard_scaler.fit_transform(features_columns)

# Create a new DataFrame with the scaled numerical columns and the original categorical columns
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(features_columns, columns=df.drop(columns=[target_column]).columns)

# Add the target column back to the scaled DataFrame
scaled_df[target_column] = df[target_column]

7. Comparing performance of svm and decision tree classifier figure out where it makes most sense to use bagging and why

Based on the performance comparison of the SVM and decision tree classifiers:

  1. SVM Models
    Both standalone and bagging SVM models show relatively similar performance in terms of accuracy and class-specific metrics. Bagging SVM has slightly lower precision and recall for class 1 compared to the standalone SVM. Bagging SVM's advantage lies in its slightly better recall for class 0.

  2. Decision Tree Models
    The bagging decision tree model outperforms the standalone decision tree model in terms of accuracy and class-specific metrics. Bagging decision tree achieves improved precision, recall, and F1-score for both classes.

Bagging is most beneficial for complex models with high variance, such as decision trees. It helps reduce overfitting and enhances the generalization of the model's predictions. In this case, the bagging decision tree model performs significantly better than the standalone decision tree in terms of accuracy and class-specific metrics. Therefore, using bagging with decision trees makes sense when aiming for improved performance.

For SVM models, the performance difference between standalone and bagging SVM is relatively small. Bagging does not provide a substantial improvement in this scenario. SVMs are already robust and less prone to overfitting compared to decision trees, so the benefit of bagging may not be as pronounced.

In summary, when deciding whether to use bagging, consider the complexity and variance of the base model. Bagging is more likely to be beneficial when applied to models with high variance, such as decision trees. For SVMs, the choice of using bagging may depend on specific requirements and trade-offs between precision and recall for different classes.
